      </div>

      <div class="grid">
        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">OpenClaw</span>
          <h2>Main boardwalk</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://discord.com/invite/clawd" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Discord</a> — the primary community dock.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/openclaw/community" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Community repo</a> — governance and public scaffolding.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Main repo</a> — code, issues, releases.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">NanoClaw</span>
          <h2>Where the tinkerers gather</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/qwibitai/nanoclaw/discussions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub Discussions</a> — best public question-and-answer dock.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/qwibitai/nanoclaw" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Main repo</a> — source, issues, README, releases.</li>
            <li>Conversation also spills into self-hosting threads and comparison posts.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">PicoClaw</span>
          <h2>Tiny-hardware harbor</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/sipeed/picoclaw/discussions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub Discussions</a> — the cleanest public square.</li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/sipeed/picoclaw" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Main repo</a> — where performance-minded discussion lives.</li>
            <li>The culture feels more code-first and less socially centralized than OpenClaw.</li>
            <li>PicoClaw Armored currently reads as a derivative/sub-version conversation on that same PicoClaw shoreline, not a fully separate public square.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">NemoClaw</span>
          <h2>NVIDIA's Claw — GTC 2026</h2>
          <p><strong>Hot off GTC 2026:</strong> NVIDIA launched <a href="https://github.com/NVIDIA/NemoClaw" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NemoClaw</a> — an open-source reference stack that runs OpenClaw inside NVIDIA OpenShell with sandboxing (Landlock + seccomp + netns) and managed inference.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Alpha preview since March 16, 2026</li>
            <li>One-command deploy: <code>curl -fsSL https://www.nvidia.com/nemoclaw.sh | bash</code></li>
            <li>Supports NVIDIA Endpoints, OpenAI, Anthropic</li>
            <li>Jensen Huang called OpenClaw "the next ChatGPT"</li>
            <li><a href="https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/ai/nemoclaw/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NVIDIA overview</a> &amp; <a href="https://github.com/NVIDIA/NemoClaw" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Main repo</a></li>
            <li><strong><a href="/nemoclaw/">Full NemoClaw page →</a></strong></li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card full">
          <span class="mini">How to use this</span>
          <h2>What to click first</h2>
          <p>If you’re new, start with the biggest clearest public dock for the project you care about. For OpenClaw, that usually means Discord plus docs. For NanoClaw and PicoClaw, start with Discussions and the repo itself. For NemoClaw, stay close to the official NVIDIA channels until the grassroots shoreline gets more defined.</p>
        </section>
